Let SHAM3 be the problem of finding a Hamiltonian cycle in a graph G = (V,E) with V divisible by 3 and DHAM3 be the problem of determining if a Hamiltonian cycle exists in such graphs. Which one of the following is true?
option1: Both DHAM3 and SHAM3 are NP-hard
option2: SHAM3 is NP-hard, but DHAM3 is not
option3: DHAM3 is NP-hard, but SHAM3 is not
option4: Neither DHAM3 nor SHAM3 is NP-hard
answer: Both DHAM3 and SHAM3 are NP-hard

question: A problem in NP is NP-complete if
option1: It can be reduced to the 3-SAT problem in polynomial time
option2: The 3-SAT problem can be reduced to it in polynomial time
option3: It can be reduced to any other problem in NP in polynomial time
option4: some problem in NP can be reduced to it in polynomial time
answer: The 3-SAT problem can be reduced to it in polynomial time
